    "summary": "El Salvador's civil war lasted from 1979 to 1992, claiming approximately 75,000 lives in a country of fewer than five million people. The conflict pitted the US-backed Salvadoran government and its military against the Farabundo Martí National Liberation Front (FMLN), a coalition of left-wing guerrilla organizations. The roots of the war lay in the extreme inequality of Salvadoran society, where a tiny oligarchy controlled the vast majority of arable land while the rural majority lived in poverty.\n\nThe war was marked by horrific atrocities committed primarily by government-linked death squads, including the assassination of Archbishop Óscar Romero in 1980 and the El Mozote massacre in 1981, in which soldiers killed hundreds of civilians. The United States provided over six billion dollars in military and economic aid to the Salvadoran government during the conflict, viewing it through the lens of Cold War competition with Cuban and Nicaraguan-supported leftists. A UN-brokered peace accord signed in Chapultepec, Mexico, in January 1992 ended the fighting and incorporated the FMLN into legal political life, initiating a fragile but ultimately lasting democratic transition.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salvadoran_Civil_War",
